The replacement of conventional cars by electric vehicles powered by high volumetric energy density Li-ion batteries (which are also used in other devices such as laptops and cell phones) is seen as one of the most significant efforts to lower anthropogenic CO2 emissions in the near future. The European Commission and Joint Research Centre189 estimated that 900 million electric cars would be manufactured by 2048. Different cathodic materials have been developed for these batteries such as190: LiCoO2, LiMn2O4 or LiFePO4 as well as Lithium Nickel Manganese Cobalt (LiNixMnyCo1-x-y\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
